Here is a minimal solution works without useEffect or changing category and products.
A few issues that can be addressed in posted code:
Each input need to have an unique id which matches htmlFor on label for the pair to work together.
When filterProducts sets a new state value, it does not get the updated value in the same block. Only use this event to set the filters in toCheck.
The value type of toCheck can an object of [category]: Boolean so each category can be filtered separately, and filters can be combined as well.
The original products can be filtered before mapped, so there is no need to keep another state of newProducts, or to modify products data.
Example (live demo: stackblitz)
import React, { useState } from 'react';
