Anyway, what you asked for is a very common error in Javascript: it means that a variable called includes, or an object with includes property, for example:
response {
  data: {
    includes: string;
  }
}
is trying to be read in your code, but either it is a declared variable which has not been initialized, or, more probably, it should be a key of an object which is not actually included in it (or maybe the object itself is undefined).
In our example, it means that response.data has not includes property, or even response has no data property at all.
If this variable comes out of an http request, this happens quite often due to distraction (for example, when one writes response.includes instead of response.data.includes). In that case, you'd better print the former variable with console.log to see what's wrong.

