Being null and having a length of 0 are different. arrs can be non-null, but still have a length of 0. That is exactly the case when you do:
getLengthAndWidth(new int[][]{});
Compare that to:
getLengthAndWidth(null);
where arrs would be null.
So you need to check both cases, and do not proceed with the rest of the method when you find the array is null or empty.
public static void getLengthAndWidth(int[][] arrs){

    if(arrs == null || arrs.length == 0){
        System.out.println("arrs is null or empty!");
        return;
    }

    // assuming all inner arrays have the same length
    System.out.println("width: " + arrs[0].length);
    System.out.println("height: " + arrs.length);

}
Now your method would not throw IndexOutOfBoundsException.
Note that this only checks if the outer array is null or empty, not the inner arrays, as you have asked. However, as you may or may not know, the inner arrays can be empty, or null, or have different lengths, i.e. I could pass in:
getLengthAndWidth(new int[][]{
    null, {}, { 1, 2, 3 }, { 1, 2 }
});
If you also want to validate the inner arrays, you should loop through each of them (e.g. with a stream or for loop), check if any of them is null and/or has a non-zero length and/or has a different length than the others.
For example, this checks that all the inner arrays are non null and non empty.
if(arrs == null || 
    arrs.length == 0 ||
    Arrays.stream(arrs).anyMatch(arr -> arr == null || arr.length == 0)){
    System.out.println("Invalid 2D array!");
    return;
}
See this post for how to validate that all the lengths of the inner array are also the same.

