First of all, when you use getElementsByTagName() you should be careful. Notice how elements is plural in the function name. So you should always carefully read the function name. When it is plural, it means you will get an array and in fact if you hover over the function in vscode you should see what the return type is.
In this case it says HTMLCollection which is like a fancy array. This means when you look for nav, although there is only one element with that tag, it gets returned in an array. So you have something like this: [theNavElementYouWant].
To retrieve that element you should index the array to get the first entry, which is at index zero, like so:
var nav = document.getElementsByTagName("nav")[0]
Secondly, your navbar's height is set to 100px by your css code. So if you want to fully hide it, you should set its top position to -100px instead of -50px.
And third, since your navbar's position is fixed, then the container below it (div element with class="container") should have position: absolute; and top: 100px; such that it displays fully under the navbar. In order to see any behaviour at all though, the container's height should be bigger than the visible area on the screen, hence for testing purposes you can add height: 2000px; as well. Since you want your navbar to show as soon as you scroll up, then you might want to set the z-index of the navbar to be higher than the z-index of the container.
In that case you might want to change the container's position as well through your javascript.
js:
/* When the user scrolls down, hide the navbar. When the user scrolls up, show the navbar */ var prevScrollpos = window.pageYOffset;
window.onscroll = function() {
    var currentScrollPos = window.pageYOffset;
    var navigation = document.getElementsByTagName("nav")[0]
    var container = document.getElementsByClassName("container")[0]

    if (prevScrollpos > currentScrollPos) {
        navigation.style.top = "0px";
        container.style.top = "100px"
    } else {
        navigation.style.top = "-100px";
        container.style.top = "0px"
    }

    prevScrollpos = currentScrollPos;
}
