As others have said, the value you get from useRouter().query is an empty object on the first render. The router also exposes an isReady flag to indicate that the router is ready to use. You can combine this with the enabled option of react-query to defer the actual request:
const router = useRouter()
const { id } = router.query

useQuery({
  queryKey: ['my-query', id],
  queryFn: () => fetchMyQuery(id)
  enabled: router.isReady
})
you could also pass Boolean(id) or !!id to enabled to just disable the query when you have no id for whatever reason.

